attributes.magic: ELF 32-bit MSB executable, MIPS, MIPS-I version 1 (SYSV), statically linked, no section header

sigma_analysis_results.rule_description: Detects programs that connect to uncommon destination ports

crowdsourced_ai_results.analysis: The binary is a DDoS botnet agent, specifically a variant of the Gafgyt (BASHLITE/Qbot) family targeting MIPS-based IoT devices. It communicates via IRC protocols (NICK, USER, JOIN) and provides an extensive command-and-control (C2) interface for executing distributed denial-of-service attacks, including SYN floods (PAN), UDP floods, HTTP floods, and STD2 floods. Notable malicious behaviors include persistence via modification of /etc/rc.local, /etc/inittab, and crontab; local process termination of competing bots/scanners (tcpdump, strace); and a reverse shell (CBACK) function that redirects stdin/stdout/stderr to a socket for remote shell access. The sample also includes system enumeration techniques by querying nvram and /etc/Model_name to identify target hardware. Relevant IOCs include the file hash d63e53a729ef27fb63f7eb4adea0ebf55ca453e1fb5c73b3ee4b0e3229df1ecd, the specific Dutch string 'Hier komt de stoofvlees met friet jongens...', and command templates like 'NOTICE %s :HTTP <target> <port> <time> <threads> </shit.php?id=>'.
